You don&#39;t really need a custom `retryCount` as the message already contains a system property called `DeliveryCount` that tracks the number of delivery (read processing) attempts. If you need to store some additional metadata between the retries, you would need to [abandon][1] your message. With Functions v2, to abandon a message you will need to use the message receiver used to receive the message. 

    public static async Task ProcessMessage([ServiceBusTrigger(&quot;myqueue&quot;)] string message,
    int deliveryCount,
    MessageReceiver messageReceiver,
    string lockToken)
    {
      //
      await messageReceiver.AbandonAsync(lockToken, 
                new Dictionary&lt;string, object&gt; { { &quot;Reason&quot;, &quot;Blah&quot; });
    }

Note that to ensure Azure Functions continues to process the message you will need to throw an exception. Otherwise, Functions by default assumes the message was processed successfully and will attempt to complete the message.


  [1]: https://weblogs.asp.net/sfeldman/azure-service-bus--abandon-with-reason

